You are developing an enterprise-grade Fuar CRM System.

This file is the REFERENCE MODULE REGISTRY.
It tracks which modules serve as structural templates for new development.
When creating a new module, you MUST check this registry first to identify the correct template.

This registry is updated as features are completed.
Consult docs/phase-1-features.md for feature completion status.

==============================
REFERENCE MODULE REGISTRY
==============================

Backend Domain CRUD Module (Primary Reference):
- Template: apps/api/src/modules/fair/
- Available after: Feature 9
- Use for: Any new domain module that needs standard CRUD operations
- Pattern covers:
  Module registration (fair.module.ts)
  Controller — HTTP layer, guards, decorators, standardized response (fair.controller.ts)
  Service — business logic, Prisma queries, error handling, pagination, sorting (fair.service.ts)
  DTOs — Zod-backed validation, z.infer type derivation (dto/create-fair.dto.ts, dto/update-fair.dto.ts)
- Modules that MUST follow this template: customer (F10), and any future domain module
- When implementing F10 (Customer): read every file in apps/api/src/modules/fair/ before writing

Backend Auth & Guard Patterns:
- Template: apps/api/src/modules/auth/
- Available after: Feature 6
- Use for: Authentication strategies, JWT guards, role-based access control
- Pattern covers: Passport strategy, guard implementation, token management, login/register/refresh/logout flow

Backend Common Utilities:
- Template: apps/api/src/common/
- Available after: Feature 3
- Use for: Global filters, pipes, interceptors, custom decorators
- Pattern covers: global exception filter, Zod validation pipe, response interceptor, @Roles and @CurrentUser decorators

Shared Package — Zod Schemas:
- Template: packages/shared/src/schemas/fair.schema.ts
- Available after: Feature 8
- Use for: Adding new Zod validation schemas
- Pattern covers: createSchema + updateSchema (partial), field-level validation, enum validation
- When adding a new schema: mirror the structure of fair.schema.ts

Shared Package — Type Definitions:
- Template: packages/shared/src/types/
- Available after: Feature 5
- Use for: Adding new TypeScript interfaces for domain entities
- Pattern covers: entity interface, create/update input types, API response wrappers

Shared Package — Utility Functions:
- Template: packages/shared/src/utils/
- Available after: Feature 12
- Use for: Adding new formatting or helper functions
- Pattern covers: formatDate, formatBudget, parseBudgetRaw, conversion rate helpers

Frontend Feature Page (Primary Reference):
- Template: apps/web/src/components/fair/ + apps/web/src/app/(dashboard)/fairs/
- Available after: Feature 18-19
- Use for: Any new feature page with list view, detail view, CRUD modals
- Pattern covers:
  TanStack Query hooks (apps/web/src/hooks/use-fairs.ts)
  Card component (FairCard)
  Form component with React Hook Form + Zod (FairForm)
  Modal integration (create/edit/delete)
  Empty state and loading state handling
- When implementing customer pages (F22-23): read fair page implementation first

Frontend Base UI Components:
- Template: apps/web/src/components/ui/
- Available after: Feature 15
- Use for: Extending or creating new base UI components
- Pattern covers: shadcn/ui extension, TailwindCSS token usage, design system compliance

Frontend Auth & State:
- Template: apps/web/src/stores/auth-store.ts + apps/web/src/lib/api.ts
- Available after: Feature 17
- Use for: Adding new Zustand stores or Axios interceptor patterns

==============================
PRE-REFERENCE PHASE (Feature 1–8)
==============================

During Features 1–8, most template modules DO NOT YET EXIST.

For these features:
- There is no existing domain module to copy from.
- Follow docs/tech-stack.md for architectural decisions.
- Follow .cursor/rules/code-standards.mdc for naming and file structure.
- Follow .cursor/rules/api-design.mdc for endpoint design.
- Follow .cursor/rules/project-architecture.mdc for layered architecture.
- Follow .cursor/rules/error-handling.mdc for exception strategy.
- Follow .cursor/rules/database-conventions.mdc for Prisma patterns.

Build with EXTRA CARE during this phase — these modules BECOME the templates.

==============================
FEATURE 9 — TEMPLATE CREATION AWARENESS
==============================

Feature 9 (Fair Module) is the FIRST standard domain CRUD module in the backend.
It MUST be designed with the explicit awareness that it will serve as the
structural template for ALL future domain modules.

When implementing Feature 9:
- Every pattern must be generalizable (no fair-specific hacks).
- File naming must follow a pattern that maps 1:1 to any domain entity.
- Service methods must demonstrate the canonical way to:
  create, findAll (with pagination/sorting), findOne, update, delete
- Controller must demonstrate the canonical way to:
  apply guards, validate input, return standardized responses
- DTOs must demonstrate the canonical way to:
  import Zod schemas from @crm/shared, derive TypeScript types
- Error handling must demonstrate the canonical way to:
  check resource existence, catch Prisma errors, throw NestJS exceptions

After Feature 9 is merged to main, this module becomes the living reference.
All subsequent domain modules (F10+) MUST mirror its structure.

==============================
REGISTRY MAINTENANCE
==============================

When a template module is completed:
- Verify the "Available after" status in this registry matches reality.

When a template module is modified:
- Consider if the change should propagate to modules that followed it.
- If yes, update all follower modules for consistency.
- If the change is structural (new file, renamed pattern), update this registry.

When a new category of module emerges that has no template:
- Add a new entry to this registry with "Available after" status.
- Build that first instance with template-creation awareness (same as F9 rule).

==============================
HOW TO USE THIS REGISTRY
==============================

When starting a new module or feature:

1. Check this registry to find the relevant template(s).
2. Check docs/phase-1-features.md to verify the template feature is completed [x].
3. If template is available: read the template module's files BEFORE writing any code.
4. List the template files in your analysis (Step 1 of feature-development-protocol.mdc).
5. Mirror the structure exactly — only domain logic should differ.
6. If the new module needs a pattern not covered by the template,
   implement it cleanly and note it for potential registry update.
7. If template is NOT yet available: follow the Pre-Reference Phase rules above.
